Hereâ€™s how you can list the best practices for IAM in AWS 

1. Follow the Principle of Least Privilege
 Always grant the minimum permissions required for users and roles to perform their tasks.

2. Use IAM Roles Instead of Access Keys
 Prefer IAM roles with temporary credentials over long-term access keys for services like EC2 or Lambda.

3. Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
 Enforce MFA, especially for sensitive accounts like administrators.

4. Regularly Rotate Credentials
 Rotate passwords, access keys, and other credentials regularly. Remove inactive keys immediately.

5. Use Managed Policies Over Inline Policies
 Use AWS managed or customer-managed policies for reusability and easier management.

6. Monitor IAM Activity
 Use AWS CloudTrail and IAM Access Analyzer to monitor and log all IAM activity for security and auditing purposes.

7. Implement Permissions Boundaries
 Use permissions boundaries to limit the maximum permissions users or roles can have, even if granted more permissions by others.

8. Leverage AWS Organizations and Service Control Policies (SCPs)
 Use AWS Organizations to centrally manage permissions across multiple accounts by applying SCPs.

9. Use IAM Groups for Permission Management
 Assign permissions to groups rather than individual users to simplify access management.

10. Limit Root Account Usage
 Limit the use of the root account and enable MFA. Avoid using the root account for everyday tasks.

11. Review IAM Permissions Regularly
 Conduct periodic reviews of permissions to ensure only necessary access is granted.

12. Use Resource-Based Policies
 When needed, apply resource-based policies, such as for S3 buckets, to manage cross-account access efficiently.

13. Implement Policy Conditions
 Use conditions in policies, like IP address restrictions or requiring MFA, for more granular control.

14. Tag IAM Resources
 Tag IAM roles, users, and policies to easily track and manage them across your AWS environment.

